Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:00.580 --> 00:00:04.520
So, my name is Kelly Chen. I consider myself a Bay

00:00:04.520 --> 00:00:07.830
Area native. I grew up in Fremont, and I'm a Genetic

00:00:07.830 --> 00:00:11.990
Counselor. And technically, I guess my title is Perinatal Genetic Counselor.

00:00:11.990 --> 00:00:15.690
So I focus on patients who are pregnant or thinking about pregnancy.

00:00:15.690 --> 00:00:19.620
&gt;&gt; And as a Genetic Counselor, are there sub disciplines like, I mean are

00:00:19.620 --> 00:00:21.970
there Genetic Counselors who focus on sort

00:00:21.970 --> 00:00:25.690
of the non perinatal aspect? Certainly, so this

00:00:25.690 --> 00:00:27.210
profession is still pretty new. I think in

00:00:27.210 --> 00:00:29.575
the beginning, there weren't that many specialties. It was

00:00:29.575 --> 00:00:33.517
either pediatrics children, and, and prenatal was the second

00:00:33.517 --> 00:00:36.732
I think, as, as soon as pregnancy tests started.

00:00:36.732 --> 00:00:39.880
And since then, there are several specialties. The big

00:00:39.880 --> 00:00:43.740
ones are pediatrics, prenatal, cancer has become the hot

00:00:43.740 --> 00:00:47.498
new thing. counselors who work in a laboratory. And

00:00:47.498 --> 00:00:50.858
then specialty counselors, who work in certain disciplines like

00:00:50.858 --> 00:00:52.548
cardiology, or neurology, or.

00:00:52.548 --> 00:00:55.265
&gt;&gt; I see. And what are the, what are the various backgrounds? Do all

00:00:55.265 --> 00:00:57.876
genetic counselors have the same academic training?

00:00:57.876 --> 00:01:00.415
Or, or, do they have diverse academic training?

00:01:00.415 --> 00:01:04.560
&gt;&gt; So, yeah. So, counselors come from a wide variety

00:01:04.560 --> 00:01:07.840
of backgrounds. they do have in common that they have

00:01:07.840 --> 00:01:11.223
to have a masters degree. And the Masters degree programs

00:01:11.223 --> 00:01:15.900
require an undergraduate, usually 4 year college. But, and some prerequisite

00:01:15.900 --> 00:01:19.690
science courses, biology, chemistry. but other than that you can

00:01:19.690 --> 00:01:22.880
be any major. So, my classmate was a psychology major.

00:01:22.880 --> 00:01:26.810
I was a genetics major. some people were completely not

00:01:26.810 --> 00:01:29.530
really into either specialty as long as they finish their courses.

00:01:29.530 --> 00:01:31.240
&gt;&gt; And did you always know you wanted to be

00:01:31.240 --> 00:01:35.060
a genetic counselor, or was this a later decision or?

00:01:35.060 --> 00:01:38.780
&gt;&gt; So, it's very interesting. I'll tell you this story, and I like

00:01:38.780 --> 00:01:41.100
to share it when I give talks, that I didn't find out about

00:01:41.100 --> 00:01:43.850
genetic counseling until about a year after I graduated

00:01:43.850 --> 00:01:48.200
from undergrad. I went to UC Berkeley, and I knew

00:01:48.200 --> 00:01:50.420
I liked science, and I really liked genetics. So

00:01:50.420 --> 00:01:54.210
I was a genetics major. And at that time, when

00:01:54.210 --> 00:01:56.940
I was going to school, the main option was

00:01:56.940 --> 00:01:59.490
to be like a physician. And there wasn't many other

00:01:59.490 --> 00:02:02.930
allied health care positions. And so, when I found out

00:02:02.930 --> 00:02:06.580
that that wasn't really what was my career path I

00:02:06.580 --> 00:02:08.660
decided to go into something totally different for a couple of

00:02:08.660 --> 00:02:12.750
years. it was only after I was really, after I had graduated,

00:02:12.750 --> 00:02:16.050
unpacked my boxes from college, that I picked up a brochure

00:02:16.050 --> 00:02:19.940
about genetic counseling. And that's how I found out about the profession.

00:02:19.940 --> 00:02:21.110
&gt;&gt; Wow.

00:02:21.110 --> 00:02:24.820
&gt;&gt; I just find it ironic just because UC Berkeley

00:02:24.820 --> 00:02:27.560
had one of the oldest genetic counseling prog, training programs

00:02:27.560 --> 00:02:29.335
at that point. They were probably, like in the first

00:02:29.335 --> 00:02:31.970
four. So it had been going on for 20, 30 years.

00:02:31.970 --> 00:02:33.460
And when I was an undergrad, I had no

00:02:33.460 --> 00:02:37.880
exposure or or knowledge about the program. And so, now

00:02:37.880 --> 00:02:39.330
I feel like every time I get a chance

00:02:39.330 --> 00:02:41.670
to give back, I, I like to promote the profession.

00:02:41.670 --> 00:02:44.720
&gt;&gt; Nice. What kind of training was involved, so once you figured out

00:02:44.720 --> 00:02:46.560
that's something you wanted. what do you

00:02:46.560 --> 00:02:48.550
do to become a genetic counselor officially?

00:02:48.550 --> 00:02:52.000
&gt;&gt; So, it's very specific. So it's usually a 2 or 3 year master's

00:02:52.000 --> 00:02:54.990
program. specifically in genetic counseling. So, all

00:02:54.990 --> 00:02:57.260
the courses are geared towards the science

00:02:57.260 --> 00:03:00.992
of genetics and counseling theory. And so, right now, I just did this

00:03:00.992 --> 00:03:01.514
[UNKNOWN],

00:03:01.514 --> 00:03:06.220
I think there are about 30 programs nationwide. So there are three in

00:03:06.220 --> 00:03:10.470
California and in other states. And so you still have to apply, take

00:03:10.470 --> 00:03:12.930
standard testing like GRE's, they're still

00:03:12.930 --> 00:03:16.480
around. And do some training like volunteering

00:03:16.480 --> 00:03:19.770
in health care settings. So I volunteered to planned parenthood for a year.

00:03:19.770 --> 00:03:20.210
&gt;&gt; I see.

00:03:20.210 --> 00:03:21.380
&gt;&gt; Doing the pregnancy tests.

00:03:21.380 --> 00:03:21.900
&gt;&gt; Cool.

00:03:21.900 --> 00:03:23.550
&gt;&gt; And then applied.

00:03:23.550 --> 00:03:25.110
&gt;&gt; Are there different certifications for different

00:03:25.110 --> 00:03:26.550
States. Like if you get trained in

00:03:26.550 --> 00:03:28.580
one State. If you're in the United States, would do

00:03:28.580 --> 00:03:31.160
have an international audience? But if you're in the United States,

00:03:31.160 --> 00:03:33.720
if you get certified, or get your degree, are you

00:03:33.720 --> 00:03:36.470
able to move and, and, and be a genetic couselor in

00:03:36.470 --> 00:03:40.112
any State? That's a really good question. So, the certification

00:03:40.112 --> 00:03:43.490
and, and the accreditation process for genetic counselors has changed. It

00:03:43.490 --> 00:03:47.810
used to be a certificate issued by a national organization,

00:03:47.810 --> 00:03:49.330
through our national organization called

00:03:49.330 --> 00:03:52.380
National Society of Genetic Counseling. and

00:03:52.380 --> 00:03:56.620
then, just probably in the past 5, 6 years, many of the states

00:03:56.620 --> 00:04:00.640
pushed for licensure so that we have a license, just like any other healthcare

00:04:00.640 --> 00:04:04.300
professional, dog groomer, hair dresser. Which

00:04:04.300 --> 00:04:06.420
would open up opportunities for billing and

00:04:06.420 --> 00:04:08.520
for status, and things. So, this states

00:04:08.520 --> 00:04:11.670
just started issuing licenses 4 years ago.

00:04:11.670 --> 00:04:14.760
&gt;&gt; I see. What do you think about the profession itself

00:04:14.760 --> 00:04:18.230
overall? Is it, is it a profession that's growing in number?

00:04:18.230 --> 00:04:20.089
and, and how is it growing, if it is?

00:04:20.089 --> 00:04:23.450
&gt;&gt; So yeah, the, the profession itself definitely is

00:04:23.450 --> 00:04:25.640
growing in number. I don't have year by year,

00:04:25.640 --> 00:04:27.650
but I think, in the very beginning, I think

00:04:27.650 --> 00:04:30.390
the first national society started in the late 70s. And

00:04:30.390 --> 00:04:34.030
then there are probably 10 to 30 members maybe,

00:04:34.030 --> 00:04:37.134
and now I think we're up to past 2,000

00:04:37.134 --> 00:04:41.520
nationwise. in the state, I'm organizing this conference coming

00:04:41.520 --> 00:04:44.120
up, so I just did some stats. In this state,

00:04:44.120 --> 00:04:47.560
there's probably about 400 licensed genetic counselors. So just to give

00:04:47.560 --> 00:04:51.600
a perspective of. We're still a small specialty, but definitely growing.

00:04:51.600 --> 00:04:54.670
&gt;&gt; Is, I, I guess this so, sort of more of the

00:04:54.670 --> 00:04:58.060
personal side, but I mean, is, do you like being a genetic

00:04:58.060 --> 00:05:00.714
counselor? Do you feel like you're helping people? What, what aspect of

00:05:00.714 --> 00:05:04.460
doing this job is probably the, the best and most fulfilling for you?

00:05:04.460 --> 00:05:06.850
&gt;&gt; I think it's a combination of things. Like this

00:05:06.850 --> 00:05:09.320
job definitely, I, I really enjoy being a genetic counselor.

00:05:09.320 --> 00:05:13.320
It really fits my niche. That, it combines my

00:05:13.320 --> 00:05:16.320
interest and my love of science, and specifically genetics

00:05:16.320 --> 00:05:20.020
and genetic conditions, with seeing patients, helping people in

00:05:20.020 --> 00:05:22.520
a health care setting. So, I've been thinking about some

00:05:22.520 --> 00:05:24.610
of these answers, that you know, the traditional role

00:05:24.610 --> 00:05:27.190
for a health care professional is a doctor. But

00:05:27.190 --> 00:05:29.030
doctors have a lot of stress, a lot of

00:05:29.030 --> 00:05:34.560
schooling. doing treatments and procedures. And I wasn't necessarily interested

00:05:34.560 --> 00:05:39.070
in that part. I was really more interested in communicating to patients. And

00:05:39.070 --> 00:05:43.050
feeling like I could help them just using my words. Or just being

00:05:43.050 --> 00:05:46.810
there for them and listening to them. So, I really feel that this

00:05:46.810 --> 00:05:51.080
profession has been a really good fit, for, for, for me and my personality.

00:05:51.080 --> 00:05:52.090
&gt;&gt; That's great.

00:05:52.090 --> 00:05:52.360
&gt;&gt; Yeah.

00:05:52.360 --> 00:05:56.470
&gt;&gt; Now you said you're a perinatal genetic counselor. So walk us through,

00:05:56.470 --> 00:06:00.470
what is like? I mean who, what kind of patient comes to you, and

00:06:00.470 --> 00:06:04.520
how does the workflow process work when they seek out a genetic counselor?

00:06:04.520 --> 00:06:07.968
&gt;&gt; So, the workflow for a perinatal

00:06:07.968 --> 00:06:09.880
genetic counselor. And paranetal is actually kind

00:06:09.880 --> 00:06:14.560
of a new phrase we created at where I work. Traditionally, the word has

00:06:14.560 --> 00:06:17.180
been prenatal. So, before birth, and then

00:06:17.180 --> 00:06:20.230
there's postnatal. And now that we're doing

00:06:20.230 --> 00:06:22.920
so much intervention before birth that affects

00:06:22.920 --> 00:06:25.450
after birth, we use the combination of perinatal.

00:06:25.450 --> 00:06:27.720
So most of the patients that I

00:06:27.720 --> 00:06:31.100
see are pregnant, actively pregnant and thinking about

00:06:31.100 --> 00:06:33.180
doing some testing to check for either genetic

00:06:33.180 --> 00:06:37.060
conditions or birth defects. sometimes we see patients

00:06:37.060 --> 00:06:38.848
before they get pregnant, but they know they

00:06:38.848 --> 00:06:42.020
want to have children and know that they might

00:06:42.020 --> 00:06:45.220
be at risk for a certain condition. So,

00:06:45.220 --> 00:06:47.730
our appointments are fairly, they're like office consultations.

00:06:47.730 --> 00:06:48.050
&gt;&gt; Mm-hm.

00:06:48.050 --> 00:06:50.530
&gt;&gt; We do a little prep-work. We might contact

00:06:50.530 --> 00:06:53.200
them on the phone and get a little family history or medical

00:06:53.200 --> 00:06:57.190
history. and then our meeting with them is probably about 40 minutes, 40

00:06:57.190 --> 00:07:02.000
to 60 minutes long. and then afterwards, if we've ordered testing or there's

00:07:02.000 --> 00:07:04.860
other appointments to make. We'll follow up and, and help patients with that.

00:07:04.860 --> 00:07:07.330
&gt;&gt; I'm really curious about the, the testing. So

00:07:07.330 --> 00:07:09.130
do patients come to you and say, I want to

00:07:09.130 --> 00:07:14.330
know what's in my genes or what I pass on, and you guys do a test for them?

00:07:14.330 --> 00:07:15.930
&gt;&gt; Yeah. So I think our patients

00:07:15.930 --> 00:07:18.430
are a little biased. I mean, I'm sure there, it seems

00:07:18.430 --> 00:07:20.720
like there, there are certainly patients out there who would say,

00:07:20.720 --> 00:07:22.710
or people out there who would say they don't want to

00:07:22.710 --> 00:07:25.720
learn, know their genetic status. And those patients we never end up

00:07:25.720 --> 00:07:29.470
seeing, because they would just decline an appointment with us. So

00:07:29.470 --> 00:07:32.110
those that we do see definitely are interested in some kind

00:07:32.110 --> 00:07:35.670
of genetic information. Whether it's for themselves or primarily for their

00:07:35.670 --> 00:07:39.520
pregnancy, or their future child. so,

00:07:39.520 --> 00:07:41.270
yeah. So, sometimes there's something specific

00:07:41.270 --> 00:07:44.710
in the family that we're looking for. We've had some patients just say, test

00:07:44.710 --> 00:07:46.840
me for everything, I want to know everything.

00:07:46.840 --> 00:07:48.920
And we have to explain the science and

00:07:48.920 --> 00:07:53.190
technology's not quite there yet. And so we're trying to pin point, what can we

00:07:53.190 --> 00:07:56.460
offer you? Accurate testing, specific testing, something

00:07:56.460 --> 00:07:59.550
that will be helpful to you. So, yeah.

00:07:59.550 --> 00:08:02.260
&gt;&gt; And what kind of what do you think about this sort of

00:08:02.260 --> 00:08:06.368
new wave of personal genetics, and, and companies that are able to you

00:08:06.368 --> 00:08:09.020
know, get samples from individuals and, and,

00:08:09.020 --> 00:08:11.160
and look at genes for them. How does,

00:08:11.160 --> 00:08:14.970
how does that fit in with this whole process of, of patients coming to you.

00:08:14.970 --> 00:08:19.450
&gt;&gt; Right. So, this whole wave of personal genomics they've

00:08:19.450 --> 00:08:24.010
called it. it's a, it's a separate court category by itself.

00:08:24.010 --> 00:08:28.450
And hasn't quite crossed in the penal realm yet. But,

00:08:28.450 --> 00:08:31.130
I mean, we certainly hear about it indirectly from our colleagues.

00:08:32.220 --> 00:08:34.210
I think e, just with our experience with the

00:08:34.210 --> 00:08:39.049
genetic testing, a lot of genetic testing is not straightforward.

00:08:39.049 --> 00:08:41.020
Sometimes we find things and we don't know how to

00:08:41.020 --> 00:08:45.780
interpret. And so, the personal genomics, I think is a,

00:08:45.780 --> 00:08:48.390
exciting new field. But also, as with any new

00:08:48.390 --> 00:08:52.890
test comes with limitation. And you know, those of us

00:08:52.890 --> 00:08:55.190
in the community of genetic counselors, some are very supportive

00:08:55.190 --> 00:08:57.320
of that technology. Some of us are still a little

00:08:57.320 --> 00:09:00.110
hesitant and cautious about, is it more harmful

00:09:00.110 --> 00:09:03.090
and helpful to start looking for things that

00:09:03.090 --> 00:09:05.660
may not have a co, complete answer to,

00:09:05.660 --> 00:09:08.000
like opening up Pandora's box kind of thing.

00:09:08.000 --> 00:09:12.030
&gt;&gt; Can you give me any examples, any specific examples of traits like that

00:09:12.030 --> 00:09:16.100
that you think are, you know, make it more difficult to really understand. Like

00:09:16.100 --> 00:09:19.420
is there a particular kind of dilemma, or is the patient ever come to

00:09:19.420 --> 00:09:22.340
you, or you felt you were in a situation where you were giving them information

00:09:22.340 --> 00:09:24.160
that they couldn't do anything with anyhow?

00:09:24.160 --> 00:09:27.710
&gt;&gt; Yeah, so there's, there's actually, so, I

00:09:27.710 --> 00:09:29.770
have a few examples. So one, one example

00:09:29.770 --> 00:09:31.720
of a test that's not straightforward, that kind

00:09:31.720 --> 00:09:34.540
of gives us a little difficulty in counseling, is

00:09:34.540 --> 00:09:37.690
maybe for a condition like hemochromatosis. So, that's

00:09:37.690 --> 00:09:40.290
an adult type onset condition, where you don't have

00:09:40.290 --> 00:09:43.229
symptoms until you reach adulthood, and it causes

00:09:44.300 --> 00:09:47.500
iron storage or overload. It can be treated fairly

00:09:47.500 --> 00:09:50.778
easily, but it does need treatment. the issue with

00:09:50.778 --> 00:09:53.040
the genetics of it is that there is a

00:09:53.040 --> 00:09:56.550
gene or two genes associated with the condition, but

00:09:56.550 --> 00:09:59.380
the gene is not the full picture. So people

00:09:59.380 --> 00:10:01.680
who have changes in the gene don't always have

00:10:01.680 --> 00:10:04.400
the condition. and so I think there's a lot

00:10:04.400 --> 00:10:08.880
of conditions like that. Alzheimer's, high cholesterol levels, where

00:10:08.880 --> 00:10:12.630
you identify a gene but it's not 100% correlation that

00:10:12.630 --> 00:10:17.040
that gene change always causes symptoms. And then you're left with not

00:10:17.040 --> 00:10:21.670
the co, not the whole picture, and you're giving probabilities. And so then

00:10:21.670 --> 00:10:25.290
the issue becomes, is that helpful to know about, know about a

00:10:25.290 --> 00:10:28.980
possibility that you may or may not be able to change or treat?

00:10:28.980 --> 00:10:29.503
&gt;&gt; Mm-hm.

00:10:29.503 --> 00:10:33.610
&gt;&gt; So that's been I think the big dilemma. The ethical dilemma is, some people

00:10:33.610 --> 00:10:37.710
would say I'd still want to know, because I want to prepare myself and try to

00:10:37.710 --> 00:10:39.630
do as much prevention as possible.

00:10:39.630 --> 00:10:40.290
&gt;&gt; Sure.

00:10:40.290 --> 00:10:43.110
&gt;&gt; Other people would say, well, if it's not for sure, I'm going to be left

00:10:43.110 --> 00:10:48.500
worrying and, and I'd rather just take it as it comes. So I think that's the big

00:10:48.500 --> 00:10:50.980
issue with the new genetic te, technologies in

00:10:50.980 --> 00:10:53.100
general. Whether it's looking for a trait or

00:10:53.100 --> 00:10:56.000
a specific condition that, most of the testing

00:10:56.000 --> 00:10:59.910
right now is not 100, 100% accurate or specific.

00:10:59.910 --> 00:11:01.120
&gt;&gt; Right. It sounds like a lot of what

00:11:01.120 --> 00:11:03.250
you end up doing as well as sort of education,

00:11:03.250 --> 00:11:07.956
patient education of traits and testing, and how to interpret various results.

00:11:07.956 --> 00:11:12.470
&gt;&gt; Definitely. So, a lot of what I do is I think of it as a

00:11:12.470 --> 00:11:16.020
consultation, but also just providing information. I see

00:11:16.020 --> 00:11:19.810
us as a link between physicians and patients, that

00:11:19.810 --> 00:11:22.570
traditionally doctors order tests that are fairly straightforward

00:11:22.570 --> 00:11:24.930
like a blood count. Or a blood type,

00:11:24.930 --> 00:11:26.790
or something like that. And they can easily

00:11:26.790 --> 00:11:28.980
tell a patient what that means in a sentence.

00:11:28.980 --> 00:11:31.650
With this genetic testing, it's much more complicated than

00:11:31.650 --> 00:11:34.910
that. it's not always a straightforward yes or no, and

00:11:34.910 --> 00:11:38.450
doctors don't have time to spend with patients explaining that.

00:11:38.450 --> 00:11:40.770
And so I see us as a bridge between that.

00:11:40.770 --> 00:11:44.420
Being able to help patients decipher and interpret this information.

00:11:44.420 --> 00:11:47.230
And then also helping them make decisions based on those

00:11:47.230 --> 00:11:50.390
results. because a lot of decisions to be made, especially

00:11:50.390 --> 00:11:54.340
in pregnancy, are not always medical decisions, they're personal decisions

00:11:54.340 --> 00:11:57.210
about what patients want to do about information, about

00:11:57.210 --> 00:12:01.400
their future offspring. so, so prenatal specifically is an

00:12:01.400 --> 00:12:04.260
interesting ethical realm, because we're also dealing with pregnancy

00:12:04.260 --> 00:12:07.640
and, and termination. What's the most difficult aspect of

00:12:07.640 --> 00:12:09.620
that if I can ask. is it, is it

00:12:09.620 --> 00:12:13.600
patients actually you know, deciding about you know, continuing

00:12:13.600 --> 00:12:17.780
the pregnancy versus not? are there significant traits that

00:12:17.780 --> 00:12:19.420
they have to deal with? I just, I'm looking

00:12:19.420 --> 00:12:21.150
for some kind of idea when it, when it does

00:12:21.150 --> 00:12:24.020
get gray as far as the difficult part of the job.

00:12:24.020 --> 00:12:25.800
&gt;&gt; Yeah, so, yeah, no you bring up a good

00:12:25.800 --> 00:12:27.880
point. I actually hadn't thought about that before. One of the

00:12:27.880 --> 00:12:31.290
difficulties in the job, in what I do with pregnancy

00:12:31.290 --> 00:12:35.890
is, we're not always we're, we're certainly talking about genetic testing.

00:12:35.890 --> 00:12:36.170
&gt;&gt; Sure.

00:12:36.170 --> 00:12:38.300
&gt;&gt; Sometimes, we're dealing with other kinds

00:12:38.300 --> 00:12:40.460
of tests in pregnancy, like ultrasounds. So,

00:12:40.460 --> 00:12:44.710
a video picture of the baby. Where you see a physical problem that might

00:12:44.710 --> 00:12:48.040
be something that suggests a genetic condition like Down Syndrome, or

00:12:48.040 --> 00:12:52.890
something else. And seeing the physical problem doesn't guarantee what the

00:12:52.890 --> 00:12:55.500
outcomes going to be. And so that is one difficulty in

00:12:55.500 --> 00:12:58.150
