00:25:15.490 --> 00:25:17.530
of our job, where it's a rare occurrence of

00:25:17.530 --> 00:25:20.220
something happening. So it's not, I don't think

00:25:20.220 --> 00:25:24.830
we've discovered a new inheritance, but we've discovered new

00:25:24.830 --> 00:25:28.480
instances of a rare, rare instances of things that

00:25:28.480 --> 00:25:31.610
can happen with traditional inheritance patterns. So that's, that's one

00:25:31.610 --> 00:25:34.460
way. Like something happens on top of something else

00:25:34.460 --> 00:25:37.680
and that's what gives that pattern. and then we can

00:25:37.680 --> 00:25:39.750
also be fooled when people are related to each

00:25:39.750 --> 00:25:43.210
other. because then that throws things, because it could be

00:25:43.210 --> 00:25:45.630
a dominant trait. But if there's relatives that are, are

00:25:45.630 --> 00:25:48.230
related to each other, it could be recessive as well.

00:25:48.230 --> 00:25:48.990
&gt;&gt; Mm-hm.

00:25:48.990 --> 00:25:49.970
&gt;&gt; and

00:25:49.970 --> 00:25:52.020
then your other question just about. I mean, we certainly

00:25:52.020 --> 00:25:56.100
have conditions that nobody's described before. And we see it

00:25:56.100 --> 00:25:58.050
in prenatal, but we see it more in pediatrics, where

00:25:58.050 --> 00:26:01.270
a child comes to us with a unique set of symptoms

00:26:01.270 --> 00:26:04.020
and that's not been described. And so that, that's a

00:26:04.020 --> 00:26:08.810
cool part of a pediatric genetics counselor's or doctor's job

00:26:08.810 --> 00:26:12.600
is they might actually identify a new syndrome. So, I

00:26:12.600 --> 00:26:15.400
haven't personally been part of that, but my colleagues actually have.

00:26:15.400 --> 00:26:18.030
And we know physicians who have discovered new

00:26:18.030 --> 00:26:20.500
conditions and have had them named after them.

00:26:20.500 --> 00:26:21.770
&gt;&gt; Wow.

00:26:21.770 --> 00:26:22.027
&gt;&gt; Yeah.

00:26:22.027 --> 00:26:27.630
&gt;&gt; That's crazy. That's pretty cool. I also wanted to know, I, you know, when

00:26:27.630 --> 00:26:31.250
I learned genetics the first time, and, as you just said a second ago, it,

00:26:31.250 --> 00:26:32.780
it happens. And you have to look

00:26:32.780 --> 00:26:35.110
for it, you're looking for maybe recessive traits,

00:26:35.110 --> 00:26:37.550
and, you see a, unaffected parents and

00:26:37.550 --> 00:26:40.840
affected children, and you're looking for, maybe, close

00:26:40.840 --> 00:26:41.510
relation.

00:26:41.510 --> 00:26:41.950
&gt;&gt; Yeah.

00:26:41.950 --> 00:26:43.600
&gt;&gt; You know, for new beginnings, new, new,

00:26:43.600 --> 00:26:45.477
new students to a class of genetics are like,

00:26:45.477 --> 00:26:48.350
has that really happened. If people find out

00:26:48.350 --> 00:26:51.530
that they actually had children can, can we speak

00:26:51.530 --> 00:26:53.290
to that all. How, how often do you

00:26:53.290 --> 00:26:56.230
people find out either, whether they knew or didn't

00:26:56.230 --> 00:26:58.536
know that they, they you know, didn't have children

00:26:58.536 --> 00:27:00.790
with somebody of a close relation. What's that like?

00:27:00.790 --> 00:27:03.210
&gt;&gt; So, I would say that the, what we

00:27:03.210 --> 00:27:06.890
call consanguinity when people are related to each other.

00:27:06.890 --> 00:27:09.990
Often, in my experience, it's not an unknown thing.

00:27:09.990 --> 00:27:12.130
I mean there a certain cultures in other countries where

00:27:12.130 --> 00:27:15.380
it's actually preferred that people marry within the family.

00:27:17.090 --> 00:27:19.200
and so, it's actually a known thing up front that

00:27:19.200 --> 00:27:21.390
they have to marry within the family to keep

00:27:21.390 --> 00:27:26.030
funding, or money, or status in the family. I have

00:27:26.030 --> 00:27:28.460
had one instance when I was talking to a

00:27:28.460 --> 00:27:31.890
patient on the phone and drawing her pedigree, that she

00:27:31.890 --> 00:27:34.180
did not know she had married either a

00:27:34.180 --> 00:27:36.310
first or se, her, her husband was her first

00:27:36.310 --> 00:27:39.160
or second cousin. And that she found out

00:27:39.160 --> 00:27:41.175
when they were invited to the same family wedding.

00:27:41.175 --> 00:27:42.700
[LAUGH]

00:27:42.700 --> 00:27:47.280
So, I mean, so, I think it doesn't happen in, for, at

00:27:47.280 --> 00:27:49.860
least for me, it hasn't happened that often where people don't know

00:27:49.860 --> 00:27:52.480
they're related to each other. Often times they're coming to us because

00:27:52.480 --> 00:27:55.860
they already know that somehow and they're worried about the risks from that.

00:27:55.860 --> 00:27:59.410
&gt;&gt; Sure. because you hear, we learn about it in textbooks,

00:27:59.410 --> 00:28:02.910
but, I'm like, what, what context does that really happen in?

00:28:02.910 --> 00:28:05.130
&gt;&gt; Or I guess not even relatedness but coming from

00:28:05.130 --> 00:28:08.500
the same community. So, for example, just people of Ashkenazi Jewish

00:28:08.500 --> 00:28:10.540
descents, and I, and I would say hopefully it's

00:28:10.540 --> 00:28:13.360
not disrespectful for anyone from that community. But I

00:28:13.360 --> 00:28:15.210
think there are a lot of communities, whether they're

00:28:15.210 --> 00:28:17.970
religious or cultural that tend to marry from that community.

00:28:17.970 --> 00:28:18.820
&gt;&gt; Sure.

00:28:18.820 --> 00:28:21.660
&gt;&gt; And it's just, I think they call it a Founder Effect. Somebody, an

00:28:21.660 --> 00:28:26.850
ancestor in that, from that gener, culture happened to carry a bad recessive or

00:28:26.850 --> 00:28:30.280
serious recessive gene like Tay-Sachs disease. And he happened to have a lot of

00:28:30.280 --> 00:28:32.160
children and those children happy, happened to

00:28:32.160 --> 00:28:33.680
marry each other. And then that condition

00:28:33.680 --> 00:28:37.920
really increased in incidents. And so that's happened,

00:28:37.920 --> 00:28:40.690
that's been known to happen in certain part pockets.

00:28:40.690 --> 00:28:40.720
&gt;&gt; Mm-hm.

00:28:40.720 --> 00:28:43.660
&gt;&gt; Of population, even if they're not related to each other. If they're a

00:28:43.660 --> 00:28:47.580
close community. So so it's fortunate or

00:28:47.580 --> 00:28:51.130
unfortunate. And, and the Jewish population in general

00:28:51.130 --> 00:28:55.650
I feel like they, they are aware of those increased risks. So many people are

00:28:55.650 --> 00:28:59.190
screened to see if they carry some of these genes, even before they get married.

00:28:59.190 --> 00:29:01.450
&gt;&gt; I see. Well, let's, let's close out here.

00:29:01.450 --> 00:29:04.978
I'm curious, let's maybe think broad aspect again, broad

00:29:04.978 --> 00:29:09.310
perspective. What what do you think other people think

00:29:09.310 --> 00:29:12.010
about genetics and genetic counseling? What do you, what, what

00:29:12.010 --> 00:29:14.050
do you think the general viewpoint is? And, and

00:29:14.050 --> 00:29:17.140
do you think that's good or bad, and should

00:29:17.140 --> 00:29:22.370
we try to change that or influence it in a certain way or is it fine on its own?

00:29:22.370 --> 00:29:24.568
&gt;&gt; So, I, I, I might,

00:29:24.568 --> 00:29:26.970
I'm al, I'm very interested in what, in what

00:29:26.970 --> 00:29:29.330
the public opinion is of genetic counseling. And I

00:29:29.330 --> 00:29:32.020
feel like we here in the Bay Area are

00:29:32.020 --> 00:29:35.060
in a very specific bubble, where we're very fortunate,

00:29:35.060 --> 00:29:38.900
we're in a very liberal area. where genetic testing

00:29:38.900 --> 00:29:43.420
is available, pregnancy termination is available. And so, I

00:29:43.420 --> 00:29:46.560
feel like the, the opinion of genetic counselors here

00:29:46.560 --> 00:29:51.100
in this area is fairly favorable. That people definitely if

00:29:51.100 --> 00:29:53.500
they have met with a genetic counselor, have definitely found it

00:29:53.500 --> 00:29:57.330
helpful and useful. I actually don't think in general nationwide. I still

00:29:57.330 --> 00:30:01.650
think it's a fairly small profession. And my sense is that,

00:30:01.650 --> 00:30:04.370
I mean, we're doing more to promote the profession, but I think

00:30:04.370 --> 00:30:06.320
there's still a lot of people who don't know what genetic

00:30:06.320 --> 00:30:09.370
counselors do and where they fit into things. A lot of patients

00:30:09.370 --> 00:30:12.500
even here, especially if they come from other countries, will hear

00:30:12.500 --> 00:30:16.440
the counseling part of genetic and think that it's a therapy session.

00:30:18.070 --> 00:30:20.560
so there's still a lot of misconceptions about what

00:30:20.560 --> 00:30:24.080
the term means. I don't think it's viewed negatively.

00:30:24.080 --> 00:30:26.060
I think it's just, it's still not very well

00:30:26.060 --> 00:30:30.000
known like other allied health professionals, professions like nurses,

00:30:30.000 --> 00:30:34.190
or social workers, or dentists. So, there's it's encouraging

00:30:34.190 --> 00:30:35.880
that there are more and more of us. And

00:30:35.880 --> 00:30:38.640
with the media being more available on the internet,

00:30:38.640 --> 00:30:43.440
hopefully we'll be promoting our profession better. and just

00:30:43.440 --> 00:30:45.920
spreading the word of the benefits of genetic counseling.

00:30:45.920 --> 00:30:50.620
&gt;&gt; Great. If you, if, if there's somebody watching right now and is really

00:30:50.620 --> 00:30:52.130
interested and wants to learn more about

00:30:52.130 --> 00:30:54.160
being a genetic counselor, what would you,

00:30:54.160 --> 00:30:57.490
do you have any particular good resource you would tell them to go visit?

00:30:57.490 --> 00:31:00.460
Or do you have any special message you would tell them about genetic counseling?

00:31:00.460 --> 00:31:04.130
&gt;&gt; So, yeah. I would, I would highly recommend that their profession if

00:31:04.130 --> 00:31:06.660
anyone's thinking about genetic counseling. it's

00:31:06.660 --> 00:31:10.040
a very good combination of medicine and

00:31:10.040 --> 00:31:12.790
health care, and interacting with patients. So we call

00:31:12.790 --> 00:31:16.270
that a clinical kind of drive, if you like patients.

00:31:16.270 --> 00:31:18.720
And if you like a specific field of genetics, because

00:31:18.720 --> 00:31:20.740
that's pretty much what we're talking about. So if you

00:31:20.740 --> 00:31:23.370
don't like genetics, I wouldn't recommend this profession. But if

00:31:23.370 --> 00:31:26.360
you want to work with people, but still be in tune

00:31:26.360 --> 00:31:30.500
with the science, it's a really good profession. and we

00:31:30.500 --> 00:31:35.310
do have a national society. So there's a website nsgc.org,

00:31:35.310 --> 00:31:37.930
that has all the information about the training programs, the

00:31:37.930 --> 00:31:41.230
background requirements. we've done professional

00:31:41.230 --> 00:31:43.580
status surveys to talk about salary,

00:31:43.580 --> 00:31:48.700
job satisfaction. genetic conselors tend to be more on the side

00:31:48.700 --> 00:31:51.880
of female. I think it's actually up to 95% are female.

00:31:51.880 --> 00:31:52.410
&gt;&gt; Holy cow.

00:31:52.410 --> 00:31:53.410
&gt;&gt;

00:31:52.410 --> 00:31:53.650
[LAUGH].

00:31:53.650 --> 00:31:55.670
So the male genetic counselors are very well known

00:31:55.670 --> 00:31:57.545
in the field because there aren't that many of them

00:31:57.545 --> 00:31:57.970
[LAUGH].

00:31:57.970 --> 00:32:03.040
Especially here in California. so, because of that, there's good

00:32:03.040 --> 00:32:05.450
and bad for that. there are a lot of counselors

00:32:05.450 --> 00:32:08.380
who work part time, and we don't take call like

00:32:08.380 --> 00:32:11.380
physicians or nurses. And so, for those again who want

00:32:11.380 --> 00:32:13.360
to go into medicine but don't want the extra stress

00:32:13.360 --> 00:32:16.580
of those kinds of things, it's a really nice profession.

00:32:16.580 --> 00:32:20.570
a lot of, lots of counselors work part time. again,

00:32:20.570 --> 00:32:23.159
because we're seeing patients and they can be scheduled appointments.

00:32:24.240 --> 00:32:27.860
the salaries I think, especially with our certification and licensure, hopefully

00:32:27.860 --> 00:32:31.875
are starting to increase. And there's certainly a lot of job opportunity.

00:32:31.875 --> 00:32:32.265
&gt;&gt; Mm-hm.

00:32:32.265 --> 00:32:34.850
&gt;&gt; So, I would highly recommend checking out the websites,

00:32:34.850 --> 00:32:38.200
and talking to a genetic counselor if you can. Even shadowing

00:32:38.200 --> 00:32:42.720
a counselor and doing some volunteer work in healthcare. Just to

00:32:42.720 --> 00:32:44.560
make sure that's the area that they like to be in.

